<div class="solution" acro="IVLT.T15">
<h5 class="solution">
<span class="type">Solution</span> <span class="acro">IVLT.T15</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.robertbeezer.knowl">Robert Beezer</a></span>
</h5>If $T$ is surjective, then <a class="knowl" acro="RSLT" type="Theorem" title="Range of a Surjective Linear Transformation" knowl="./knowls/theorem.RSLT.knowl">Theorem RSLT</a> says $\rng{T}=V$, so $\rank{T}=\dimension{V}$ by <a class="knowl" acro="ROLT" type="Definition" title="Rank Of a Linear Transformation" knowl="./knowls/definition.ROLT.knowl">Definition ROLT</a>.  In turn, the hypothesis gives $\rank{T}=\dimension{U}$.  Then, using <a class="knowl" acro="RPNDD" type="Theorem" title="Rank Plus Nullity is Domain Dimension" knowl="./knowls/theorem.RPNDD.knowl">Theorem RPNDD</a>,
\begin{equation*}
\nullity{T}=\left(\rank{T}+\nullity{T}\right)-\rank{T}=\dimension{U}-\dimension{U}=0
\end{equation*}
With a null space of zero dimension, $\krn{T}=\set{\zerovector}$, and by <a class="knowl" acro="KILT" type="Theorem" title="Kernel of an Injective Linear Transformation" knowl="./knowls/theorem.KILT.knowl">Theorem KILT</a> we see that $T$ is injective.  $T$ is both injective and surjective so by <a class="knowl" acro="ILTIS" type="Theorem" title="Invertible Linear Transformations are Injective and Surjective" knowl="./knowls/theorem.ILTIS.knowl">Theorem ILTIS</a>, $T$ is invertible.
</div>
